text: A lot of food he ate in Myeongdong is something I, as a Korean, have never seen before. It is different from the street food commonly eaten in Korea. text:
I was thrilled to see the Cathedral!
My father was in Korea during the war. I recently found his slide pictures from his time there and have been researching to identify the places he had been.
So far I have found three places that I know where my father had been. This Cathedral is one them, and Namsan Hill.
My father never talked about his time in Korea and sadly has passed.
My plan now is continue to research and find the locations of my father's pictures. Then in Sept 2025, with my son, we will walk in my father's foot prints to re-create the same pictures that he took over 70 years ago.

text:
I am a korean and I can give a tip on traveling to Korea as a Korean to foreigners who are going to visit Korea watching this video, use Kakao Map instead of Google Map. There are many reviews that Google Map does not work well. Kakao Map is a map that Koreans use a lot and provides more accurate information.
Also, I see it in the comments a lot, also I don't recommend Myeongdong. It is very expensive for the value of the food or the items. Hongdae is recommended, which is affordable and is a place enjoyed by many locals. Also, Korean food culture does not have appetizers in particular, and many side dishes and soups are eaten with rice, unlike in Western countries. Watching foreigners' vlogs on their trip to Korea, I felt sorry  for  that they ate soup and side dishes first, and then ate. Lastly, I recommend you to try galbi and franchise tteokbokki. Galbi is a sweet Korean barbecue and tteokbokki is a stir-fried rice cake with spicy sauce. It is one of the favorite foods of young Korean women. Each place has very different flavors. If you want to eat traditional tteokbokki, I recommend eating it with fish cake sold in the market or on the street. If you want to provocative tteokbokki, which is  provocative  and is favored by young Korean women, try franchise tteokbokki . Franchise tteokbokki has a strong fusion flavor, usually cheese. If you are worried about it being spicy, try rosÃ©-tteokbokki. It has been popular for a few years, it is much less spicy, soft, and greasy.

text: Among the traditional places, I  recommend Gyeongbokgung Palace . You can rent a hanbok from a nearby hanbok store and walk around Gyeongbokgung Palace and its vicinity. Also, one of the ways to eat delicious kimchi is to eat cooked kimchi. Most of the time, kimchi is a side dish that is eaten with rice like pickles, but people like it or dislike it because of the seafood and texture in making kimchi. I don't  like normal kimchi either. But I like cooked kimchi when I eat Korean barbecue,  kimchi cooked together,kimchi fried rice, or stew. If you want to try kimchi, but you are worried about it, try cooked kimchi

text: I've been living in Seoul since I was born, but not all prices are the same in Seoul. The prices in Myeongdong are literally crazy and they sell it at a high price to foreign tourists, so Koreans don't buy it. And you don't have to fasten your bag forward. This is not Africa haha. There is no pickpocket in Korea. Because there is no one who can't live enough to starve to death. Since we are a capitalist country, there is a lot of support from the country, and ordinary people live well. Wi-Fi is popular on the subway, bus, or street, so it is hard to find a place without Wi-Fi, and even in the countryside, Wi-Fi is often available. Many people see it similar to Japan and China. Actually, it is quite different.

text: I'm married to a Korean and absolutely LOVE South Korea (the funniest part is that as a Soviet kid, I got to go to NORTH Korea with my Pioneer Unit - it seems I was always destined to be connected to Korea). The people, the food, the Soju, the FOOD LOL Every time we go, it's like taking a time machine forward 25 years. No American city can compare to Seoul. Our last trip to SK, the people sitting next to us - young people - seem to be expecting a dirty 3rd world country (I swear, their image of South Korea is from old MASH re-runs LOL). I watched them in the aeroport and it was highly amusing to see their jaws drop. Love that you just wandered so you shared a lot of place like you did! Very cool. I'll be watching the rest of these videos after, but just in case - your TMoney card is usable all over the country, not just Seoul (which is AMAZINGLY wonderful and brilliant!!!). Anyone who hasn't tried Soju - DO IT DO IT DO IT! It's wonderful! It's becoming a lot more easily available in the US (though a bottle that costs $1.25 in SK runs $6.99-8.99 here lol - but WORTH IT). Zane, I hope they showed you how to Tornado your Soju, or got you Somaeks (last night, in fact, we did Titanic-Ju! Someaks - Soju dropped into beer whilst yelling TITANIC! lol). Anyhow... this made me very happy. Thank you for sharing SK with the world, Zane!

text:
Hello, Zane and all kinds of people to visit korea. Welcome! ë°˜ê°€ì›Œìš”!!
If you want to enjoy korea culture and food, you have to divide the travel theme for two theme. So first, if you are interested in tradition, enjoy a tour of "Hanok" or palace from day to night. I recommend "Gyeongbokgung". Next, I recommend the "Gwangjang Market" in Jongno to enjoy the traditional market. Enjoy Korean style raw beef called yukhoe and jeon. But I don't recommend snack foods. If you want to get snack food, use the street franchise. I'm sure it's more fresh and savory. 
And for the second, I recommend you to enjoy Korean drinking culture or night streets. As you know, Korea has very good in security, so it is better to play at night than other countries. There are Hongdae, Itaewon, Euljiro 3-ga, Apgujeong, and Gangnam and so on,,,  but there are many foreigners in Hongdae or Itaewon, so you will be able to play more comfortably. You can make new friends and enjoy your freedom. However, always be careful of getting wasted. Then you can use the police station as your accommodation :(
And when it comes to decent restaurants, even if you go to places like Myeongdong, I recommend you surf the Internet or ask the local Koreans. But frankly, I don't recommend Myeongdong, because Euljiro 3-ga near Myeongdong is a hot place. Anyway Most of young Koreans know famous places very well, so they will recommend restaurants that you will be satisfied with. No matter where you go, there is a local decent restaurant. There are a lot of good places even near your airbnb, Chungmuro. However, it is difficult for foreigners to find it because there are themed streets in every corner, so if you ask any local Koreans, they will kindly guide you. And if you have any questions about trips in Korea, please leave a comment. I'll tell you as much as I know. Then, I hope you have a fun trip in Korea! :)

text: The reason why you hardly find rubbish bins on the streets in Korea is that Korean governments have placed the strictest rules on garbage collections in the world. So every household must sort out its own rubbish into different categories before throwing them into the bins provided in each individual home. If rubbish bins were provided all over streets it would most likely end up in piles of rubbish around them without proper sorting-out process. What is worse it would also cost a fortune for city councils to clean them up.

text: The reason public transportation in South Korea is really affordable is because the majority of it is funded by taxes. Even taxi services often receive support from the government, making public transportation very inexpensive. However, the cost of other services is higher than in Japan, and the prices at supermarkets are much more expensive. This is because the actual after-tax monthly income per person in South Korea is much higher.

text:
Welcome to my hometown and home country! I love Seoul and I'm very, very glad you do too. Korea is far from just Seoul though -- lots of other wonderful places to visit. My favourites are the other staples Busan (plus some regions more inland), Incheon, and Jeju as well as other "lesser known" places like Yeosu, Gyeongji, Jeonju, Seoraksan Nat'l Park... all great gems.

Edit: Also the subway systems (for places with one) are very nice. Clean, timely (most of the time anyway lol), and well organised.

text: Well, that's the thing. From my observation, having been living around Koreans most of my life, they don't show it but they go behind your back and make racist comments and they mean it (not in a joke or over generalizing form). I felt so bad for some people cause they didn't realize that a lot of what the Koreans show to foreign people can be fake on the outside. Let me give you an example, me and a few Korean guys hanging out, a pretty Filipino girl comes over, talks to the guys. After she left I said, "She seems to like you. Why don't you go on a date with that girl?" Then he said "Are you fucking kidding me? She's Filipino, Jesus. I can fuck one, but I won't date one." True story. Many Koreans might not admit to this kind of stories but I can guarantee it happens all the time; male and female alike. I was just one of those guy who just said nothing, but I saw it all happening. I kind of stopped hanging out with Koreans after that. Plus, I found out they've been bad mouthing me too when I wasn't around too. Just revealing the truth to you that's all. Again, I can't say all, cause I met a few great people. But in general, I would say around 70~75% of them are like this. The society looks very open and friendly, but it's actually secretly toxic. On top of that many of the K-drama that was made to criticize social issues, they aren't just drama it's real and it happens all the time.  Again, I'm just stating some of my personal experience and observation. It's your decision to believe it or not. Thanks.

text:
35:00 We call that rice cake was not cheese! Fried rice cakeğŸ˜†
I really enjoyed your video and hope you could enjoy many kinds of Korean foods!
I recommend you to reach out to other places than myeong-dong. The street foods and stores are targeted for foreigners consumers so we usually do not eat there.
Fried chicken..ummâ€¦I would like to recommend you BHC, NENE-Chicken or BBQ(you can find them in every steps!)

Here are few other recommends for you to visit from local.

-Transportation
As you already have your t-money card, itâ€™s a lot easierğŸ˜Š
You can transfer to other transportations(Bus,Metro) in an hour from your last tagging with out any additional charge.(Long distance journey might usually costs less than 50cents.)

-Mega Coffee(1 jumbo-sized cup of coffee is less than $2)
Every drinks taste pretty good! 

- Hong-dae (Hongik university station) , there are many things to enjoy! I hope you to go there and experience Korean night culture!
Tips) there are two main streets. One to the south, and other to the north. Just walking along the street might be great enough.

- Gwang jang market
As I know, many travelers plan to visit there for the priority. However, I have good memories there too! It might be a good chance to enjoy korean foods in reasonable price.

-Kyeong bok palace
Not only it has itâ€™s own historical meanings, but also the area near Kyeong bok palace has itâ€™s intrinsic vibe. Moreover, there are many Korean restaurants that serves dishes in good quality.

Hope that Iâ€™m not too lateğŸ¥°

text: From what I have seen in this video it seem like seoul is a typical mega cities of east asia on the same class as tokyo, beijing and shanghai in term of development level and tech. Tokyo is slightly behind as it has older infrastructure and shanghai slightly more advance as it has newer infrastructure and tech, but overall i would say they are the future cities....very far from it. Future cities now is represented by newer chinese mega cities such as shenzhen, hangzhou and probably xiongan which is still under construction. The level of tech throughout the city is at much higher level than the contemporary cities mentioned before. These new cities also has a much more vibrant economy as their population are made up of young migrants that work efficiently, extremely tech savy and very foward looking.

text:
25:20 Korean Christianity is just the same protestantism of America. Catholic is the same as well. They don't worship their ancestors. It's not a fusional religion of Buddhism or any other traditional Korean religions. Of course there are also Buddhists, Shamanists, and the traditional ancestor worshipers(Confucianists) in Korea, but those religions are seperate. 

Also, the traditional ancestor worshiping has an exact name of it; Confucianism. Most part of all ancestor worshiping in East Asia(Korea, China, Japan, Vietnam) is based on the ideology of Confucianism. There are justifying logics behind worshiping ancestors, but today most of people forgot about that and only some Asian philosophy major students and doctors know those doctrines. Worshiping ancestors might sound primitive to outsiders, but their doctrine is actually very sophisticated. Well, I'm a Christian though.

text: Seoul's my favourite city on the planet, once you've been you don't see the rest of the world the same way. Extremely modern, clean & safe, the best food and also has the best people. Koreans go out their way to make sure you feel welcome and have a good time. Always an amazing atmosphere wherever you are in the city. Whether it's being around the bouncing nightlife districts or chilling in the park at night having some chicken & beer. Can't wait to go back, hoping to live there full time next year

author: @WorldTaxAndy

text: â€‹Â @WorldTaxAndyÂ  I haven't lived in Japan but I would be interested to see a comparison video between living in both countries from a Western perspective. I've lived in Korea for almost 3 years, and plan to stay for 1-2 more. I will say that although Seoul is an amazing city, the real beauty of Korea is in the countryside. Be sure to visit Yangyang, Danyang, Jeju, Buyeo, Seoraksan, Seobaeksan etc. Most of the country is mountainous and many Koreans love hiking and camping.

text: â€‹@alexshen9543 The reason why South Koreans don't see u as Korean is very simple. Before we(south Koreans) used to think that if your blood is Korean, you are Korean regardless of your nationality. But that doesn't apply anymore. We think passport(meaning nationality) decides that person's identity. For example, you are Korean decendant but hold Chinese passport(nationality), you are considered Chinese. For another example, If a white or black guy holds Korean passport, Koreans think that person is Korean regardless of skin color. If you change your nationality from Chinese to Korean, no matter what South Koreans think of you as Korean. If a Korean American guy holds American Passport, Koreans think of him as American, not Korean. Do u understand what I am saying? South Koreans simply view someone's identity based on nationality(passport), not based on blood. My husband, for example, is Korean American, and he is considered American in South Korea. If a Korean Japanese holds Japanese passport, that person is considered Japanese in Korea. It's just as simple as that. There are many foreigners who hold Korean nationality nowadays, and they are considered Korean in the Korean society. So if you change your nationality from Chinese to Korean, meaning if you hold Korean passport, you are just Korean. It is a very simple concept. I actually know some Korean Chinese who changed their nationality from Chinese to Korean, and they are treated just like any other Koreans. So for most Koreans thesedays, it is ultimately the color of our passport that decides who is Korean.

text: Yeah, that definitely wasn't cheese, those were rice cakes they call "tteok". I've usually seen them in tteokbokki, rice cakes lathered in spicy sauce often eaten with fish cakes, sausages, hard boiled eggs, and various fried foods. It makes sense they'd throw some in with fried chicken, the spicy sauce is similar for tteokbokki and chicken, even though I've seen different kinds of tteokbokki with different rice cakes sizes, or sauce thickness. I've had tteok in Korean black bean sauce, but have always wanted to try other non-spicy ways to eat them like that sweet one you tried.

text: South Korea is just 20 years before version of Japan in all respects. you should rather go to Japan than to South Korea. South Korea has no historical sites or cultural heritage to see as everything was burned to ashes by the Korean War in the past. All that exist now are recently reconstructed fakes. On the other hand, Japan all cultural assets survived in Kyoto in World War II, and old historical sites exist everywhere. Traveling to South Korea is a waste of money. It is much more beneficial to go to Japan.

text: "Folk religion" you mentioned is driven from Confucianism and unlike western religion. Ancestors are considered as spirits that looks after you and not almighty god that can do everything. Hey, some western church goers also believe in their parental spirits. That is why Korean Catholic church has actually acknowledged - facing local strong resistance to drop the practice - and allowed ancestor serving practice in Korea while going to the Catholic church at the same time. Koreans only practice ancestor serving on the dates of demise and big holidays, not on weekly basis. Presbyterian church, which is the dominant church is more strict and do not allow it. Nowadays, many people do not even believe spirits and it shed most similarity with religion except for elderlies. Therefore, serving ancestors is more of a customary tradition than a religion

text: @33:03 the reason why he didn't let you put that in the trash.  Korea is really good about separating their trash.  There are different trash bags you must buy and throw only those things... Like food waste, paper goods, etc....i dunno but i think it really cuts down on how much people waste.  If you have to pay for your trash bags, you won't make too much unnecessary trash.  I remember this back in 1999.  And they had already banned plastic bags at grocery stores... Which i thought was so cheap of them back then but now that is how it is in the US... At least California.  Korea was always ahead of their time.

text:
Lovely video! Enjoyed watching it. Welcome!

0. Foreign map apps don't work in Korea due to national defence policies. 'Naver map' have more shops registered than 'Kakao map'.

0. The wall pad turns on when someone pushes the door bell from out side or when someone(from building manager) calls you.

1. Unfortunately towels are not divided into different sizes in Korea. High level hotels provide them to suit the global needs, but ordinary Koreans are fine to use that size for any use.

2. Some annoying Koreans trash their household rubbish in public rubbish bins. That's one of the reasons why rubbish bins are not around. Also throwing away each type of rubbish is different in Korea. Many Koreans hold their daily rubbish until they get home(apartment) where they can distribute the different type of rubbish.

3. The chicken you got from the street is Dak-Gang-jeong(ë‹­ê°•ì •) which kind of means chicken snack/nuggat. When Koreans say 'Chi-Mec(Chicken and Beer)', we noramlly refer to freshly fried proper chicken. (And the "cheese" you ate is tteok(ë–¡) which is rice cake).

*The best Korean fried chicken : The ones in University Areas or Local Office Areas where locals go (There are many franchise brands but it really depends on the person who fries).

*Koreans pair their food with appropriate alcohol drink.

4. Myeongdong has been dominated by tourists and transformed to a tourist place over the last 10 years. The shops, street food, items, manner are not quite native.

5. You can top-up your transportation card in subway stations too. 

6. We tend to drink soju the whole shot(especially the first glass). Afterwards you could sip half/half if you like.

text: As a Korean born and raised in Seoul (and has been living in Seoul over 50 years ğŸ˜Š), I have to tell you that Seoul is simply too vast to explore in a few days.  Even for me (someone with over 50 years of living experience in this big city), there are some areas that I heard about but have never been to, or have not been to since 1990's ğŸ˜… -- that's how big and varied this city is!  My advice is that even when you are mistreated (which could happen), or were not satisfied with the city (which could also happen), keep in mind that what you experienced in a few days may not be the complete representation of Seoul. Just like any othe big cities in the world (e.g., New York, London, Tokyo), there are dark sides and bright sides.  FYI, the total size of New York City (according to Wikipedia) is 778.2 square kilometers (300.46 square miles) and that of Seoul is 605.21 square kilometers (376 square miles). But having lived in both Seoul and New York City, I believe that Seoul is bigger in terms of size -- I don't know how Wikipedia got such numbers ğŸ˜…

text: You do realize that MyeongDong is the worst place for Korean street food.  It's a very touristy neighbourhood.  You probably didn't notice but most of the people, including the crowd, vendors, store staff are non Koreans; chinese, japanese, south east asians.  Locals don't really hang out at MyeongDong anymore.  The food is terrible.  Branch out to more authentic neighbourhoods and avoid the touristy places.  BuamDong is a nice quiet neighbourhood with many quaint cafes, nature, galleries, small museums and a walk up the mountain through some scenic and historical sites.  It's in GangBuk on the orange line Juksangdong station (not far from Chungmuro St.) then you can take a bus to BuamDong.  Ask someone.  These are the treasures that most tourists don't get to see. Seoul has become so overcome with touristy and modern amenities that sometimes you won't feel like you are actually in a different country.

text: I just did a solo trip to Seoul and Tokyo/Kyoto (got back yesterday). The culture and UX of Seoul is unmatched. Everything I experienced like the cafe hopping, dining, attractions (Banpo River at night) and even places like Pokpo Cafe from IG were just as good if not even better in real life. I felt Tokyo was overrated and very westernized for my interests with a lot of attractions feeling very overhyped in-person (Tsukiji Market,  Akihabara at night was run down and boring, arcades had the same mediocre games in every single one lol, shopping and fashion was very similar to the US, mad depressing salarymen on the subways with happy go lucky tourists next to them... such a weird vibe). Kyoto was charming and beautiful with a lot of character that Tokyo was missing. Anyways, I digress but I agree Seoul is precious. Let the tourists stay in Tokyo LOL.

text: Â @Dima-xu2qwÂ  I understand your viewpoint.  I agree that Koreans don't place the same expectations upon foreigners as they do upon other Koreans, so yes, that can cause both experiences to be different.  As an American, I feel the same when people  from other countries talk about how much they want to live in the U.S. because they love the show "Friends."  Having lived in other countries outside of the U.S., I often feel so disappointed with how things are here, such as the gun violence, the woke politics, the health care system, and lack of safety.  Gun violence is a big problem in America.   The gun violence problem in America probably parallels the suicide problem in Korea.  No country is perfect.  America works for some and not others; same as Korea.  I know many Koreans who've left Korea for their own personal reasons and that's okay.  I think the goal is to live where we feel we can thrive best.

text:
Tokyo's "Subway" isn't that complex, however there's not just one, but two (Tokyo Metro and Toei Subway).Â 

Secondly, a lot of people throw around terms like "Metro" (like Zane does) or "Subway" to encompass a cities entire rail system. The thing is that "Subway" barely encompasses Tokyo's rail network. You've still got a TON of surface rail operated by over a dozen rail companies to factor.

In addition, Tokyo rail operations have a lot of different varieties of service. Many lines are operating not only local services, but also 1-4 different levels of express service. On top of that, Tokyo does the most aggressive through-operations in the world where you have multiple rail companies sharing lines. For example, on the Toei Asakusa line (a subway line), you'll see Keikyu trains from Haneda Airport, and Keisei trains from Narita airport all operating on it. Thus you kind of have to learn the difference between a "Train" (which is more of a service), and a "Line" which is a corridor that can operate many trains.

Some confusion may also arise simply because a lot of the larger stations in Tokyo have numerous connections to a lot of lines,  which can be a bit daunting to the uninitiated. For example, Otemachi (a pure subway station) connects to 5 different subway lines (as well as Odakyu's Romancecar train stopping there). Then there's the much larger stations like Shinjuku, Tokyo, Ueno, and Ikebukuro often have connections to 7+ lines and often over a dozen different trains. Even my local station of Shinagawa (which doesn't have a single subway line), still has like 4 JR lines (Yamanote, Keihin-Tohoku, Tokaido, and Yokosuka lines, 5 lines if you include Ueno-Tokyo line), plus the Keikyu Main line, and the Tokaido Shinkansen. On top of that there's additional trains that operate on those lines (Hitachi and Tokiwa, Odoriko, and the Narita Express). That can be a lot to digest. Especially for western eyes who aren't used to the sheer information density of East Asian signage. It can be a bit of sensory overload.

Lastly, Tokyo is just performing rail operations on a completely different scale than anywhere in the world. You could add up all the annual passenger traffic from Seoul Metro, Korail lines, Incheon Metro, and the Shinbandung lines, and it wouldn't even equal the passenger traffic of Tokyo Metro alone, let alone Tokyo Metro and Toei Subway combined. If you add up all the rail operators in the Seoul operations listed above, plus the Beijing Subway, the Shanghai Subway (the two largest subway networks in the world), Shenzhen Subway, and throw in New York Subway for good measure combined, it still wouldn't equal the trackage or annual passenger volume of the Tokyo urban rail network.

text: I am Korean. The best places for foreigners to visit in Seoul . Myeongdong(your video now), Hongdae is the most popular club district and pub for Koreans and foreigners, Gangnam is the largest downtown area in Korea, and it is a place of choice for foreigners who don't like many foreigners. However, prices are on the high side. It is the equivalent of Ginza in Japan. Gwangjang Market is a traditional Korean market and a place with a lot of food, and I watched a lot of videos taken by Westerners. Compared to Myeongdong, there are many traditional Korean foods that foreigners will like. I've never been to Busan, but I know it's the second most preferred place for Westerners after Seoul. It is the second largest city in Korea. Welcome to Korea :)

text: It is true that Japan is also an attractive country. However, foreigners feel very excluded in Japan. Because Japanese people do not reveal their true feelings, it is very difficult to know what they are thinking. Even if they are dissatisfied with you, they will be smiling on the outside. Additionally, transportation is quite expensive, and the subway system is complex, making it easy to get lost. Above all, there are few Japanese who can speak English. Since there is almost no written information in English, you will find it quite difficult to travel.

text: Zane! The korean alphabet is one of the easiest scripts in the world to learn how to read! It takes less than an hour to learn how to read korean! Sejong the Great had the script created specifically to make reading easier and replace chinese characters. Of course, you won't know what the words mean, but a lot of korean words come from english so you might understand more than you think! I highly recommend watching some youtube videos that teach you how to read this beautiful script.

text:
What ?!    The Ancient Korean Delicacy  The breaded  HOTDOG  and  a bag of Pomegranate Juice??
 No.   Find an English speaker and get out of the City if you want Korean Culture.
If you ever do eat actual Korean food, and it is smothered in Cheese, know that there was no cheese in Korea 
until a Belgian Monk served it to a Korean President in the late 1960's. The Korean President asked Father Didier t`Serstevens to help start the cheese industry in Korea.  Recently the Belgian catholic was granted South Korean citizenship. It does completely ruin the authenticity of the traditional food, but it is put on everything
